06908nam a22008775i 9780824887070DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20211977hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248870707 a10.1515/97808248870702doi  a(DE-B1597)572094  a(OCoLC)1253313560  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aSOC0520002bisacsh00aCommunication Research—A Half-Century Appraisal /ced. by Lyle Nelson, Daniel Lerner. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2021] 4c©1977  a1 online resource (360 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEast-West Center Books00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tI. STATE OF THE ART -- tCOMMUNICATION AND EDUCATION -- tYesterday's and Tomorrow's Television Research on Children -- tOn Mass Communication Experiments and the Like -- tCommunication and Education in Open Learning Systems -- tHow Should a University Be? -- tCommunication and Development -- tNetwork Analysis of the Diffusion of Innovations: Family Planning in Korean Villages -- tCommunication and Development -- tCommunication Policy and Planning for Development: Some Notes on Research -- tCommunication Issues -- tPublic Television: Too Much Ambition and Overcommitment? -- tMass Media Effects: New Research Perspectives -- tPopular Culture -- tCOMMUNICATION AND POLICY -- tCommunication Research and Its Applications: A Postscript -- tTechnology and Policy in the Information Age -- tBuilding as Political Communication: The Signature of Power on Environment -- tII. A LIFE IN COMMUNICATION RESEARCH -- tThe Early Years -- tThe Literary Years -- tThe Iowa Years -- tThe Illinois Years -- tThe Stanford Years -- tThe Hawaii Years -- tBibliography of the Works of Wilbur Schramm -- tCurriculum Vitae of Wilbur Schramm -- tNotes on Contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCommunication research, a relatively new field of scholarly endeavor, began about fifty years ago with some of the pioneering studies by Paul Lazarsfeld and others. Today it has become central to almost all national development efforts and to studies of the organizational structures of industrial societies.In what has been termed by many scholars the "Age of Communication," it is timely and appropriate that an appraisal be made of past accomplishments and failures as the basis for determining future directions and potential of communication research. This book makes such an appraisal and assesses the present state of the various areas of communication research. Written by world authorities in the major areas of communication research, chapters cover the diversity of the field: the impact of modern communication on traditional cultures and the spread of "open learning" systems; intriguing ideas such as that of Charles E. Osgood, whose "How Should a University Be?" provides a blueprint for reorganizing the university, and that of Harold D. Lasswell, whose "Building as Political Communication" views architecture as symbolic of power and shows how building has been manipulated to reinforce power.It is fitting that this book be dedicated to Wilbur Schramm, whose contributions, perhaps more than those of any other person, have brought the field of communication research to international prominence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh1 aChaffee, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChu, Godwin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHawkridge, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHimmelweit, Hilde, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHudson, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.